choices.text:
that I am squeezed into the middle of two generations. My father is Chinese while my mother is American. My siblings and I were raised in the United States and speak near-flawless English and almost undecipherable Mandarin. So I challenge those mainland Chinese and Taiwanese that say that, “if you want to be American, don’t talk so much Chinese.”

I’m proud of my culture and where I come from. I don’t see any reason why I should shame myself. There is a reason why my siblings and I can speak English when a large part of mainland Chinese kids cannot. After seeing how Americans get treated versus how others get treated, I really don’t want my children to grow up there. Asians are seen as weird there, and it’s ok to ostracize us if we’re not exactly like everybody else. As for living in Taiwan, I’ve got my reasons for that, and they all center around why living in America is terrible for people like me. Asians are disproportionately placed in modern day slavery through 3rd world sweat shops. When I have a family I will not raise them in a place where I know they will be unsafe from violent crime. I won’t subject my wife to a society where it is socially acceptable for men like Donald Trump to openly hate her because of her race, and a society where she automatically has an inflated rate of having diseases such as diabetes and heart disease due to changing the traditional eating lifestyle due to adopting western food culture.

S
